The Telegraph - Calcutta : International
 Thursday, July 15, 2004 				 Baghdad bomb kills 7
																								Baghdad, July 14 (Reuters): A suspected car bomb in central Baghdad killed at least 11 people, all believed to be Iraqis, today sending burning wreckage across a wide area and a plume of black smoke rising above the city.																								A US soldier at the scene of the blast said he had seen seven dead, but said that number could rise. Scores of people, including Iraqi civilian workers and reporters waiting to attend a news conference, were waiting to get into the heavily defended Green Zone when the bomb went off.																								The Green Zone is a huge, heavily defended complex on the banks of the Tigris river in central Baghdad which houses the interim Iraqi government, US and British diplomatic missions and is the headquarters for many foreign contracting companies. Doctors at the Jomal Asveyah hospital near the Green Zone received one dead man, his body burnt beyond recognition. Governor dead																								Gunmen killed the governor of the Iraqi city of Mosul and two of his bodyguards today as he was driving in a convoy of vehicles towards Baghdad. The assailants threw a grenade at the vehicle carrying the governor, Osama Kashmoula, and fired automatic weapons
